<subSubSection id="63DA72B09F31FFDAD4A15FE47E2E9573" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2B7F213B9F31FFDAD4A15FE47E2E9573" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,581]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD4A15FE47D59978E" bold="true" box="[189,593,158,184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Distribution, habitat, and ecology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD6685FE47C73978E" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" box="[628,891,158,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD6685FE47C73978E" box="[628,891,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Schwenckia aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a restricted distribution, known only from an unusual ecosystem regionally called Furados, at Serra Azul Biological Reserve in the northern 
<collectingRegion id="E904EFD99F31FFDAD0AE5FB87A4197EA" box="[1202,1353,194,220]" country="Brazil" name="Minas Gerais" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Minas Gerais</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation id="B3FB3DBE9F31FFDAD1445FB87A9697EA" box="[1368,1438,194,220]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1865,1887]" captionTargetBox="[202,1435,658,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-229@5.[151,1436,605,1841]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Schwenckia aurantiaca distribution and habitat. (A) Map showing Furados (triangle), the site of the species occurrence in northern Minas Gerais, (B) Caatinga seasonally flooded during the wet season, with a view of the calcareous outcrops, (C) Caatinga with Cavanillesia umbellata Ruiz &amp; Pavón in the Serra Azul Biological Reserve, disturbed by fire during the dry season in 2007. Photographs by J.R Stehmann." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425904/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The typical vegetation is the arboreal Caatinga where 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD6F85F9C7A109637" authority="Ruiz &amp; Pavon (1798: 166)" authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pavon" authorityPageNumber="166" authorityYear="1798" box="[740,1304,230,257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Cavanillesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umbellata">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD6F85F9C7CE19636" box="[740,1001,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Cavanillesia umbellata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="4F515CCA9F31FFDAD7EC5F9C7A109637" author="Ruiz, H. &amp; Pavon, J." box="[1008,1304,230,257]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" refId="ref5075" refString="Ruiz, H. &amp; Pavon, J. (1798) Systema vegetabilium florae peruvianae et chilensis, characteres prodromi genericos differentiales, specium omnium differentias, durantionem, loca natalia, tempus florendi, nomina vernacula, vires et usus nonullis illustrationibus interspersis complectens. I - VI. Gabriel de Sancha, Madrid, 456 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 887" type="book" year="1798">Ruiz &amp; Pavón (1798: 166)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD13B5F9C7AAC9637" box="[1319,1444,230,257]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malvaceae</taxonomicName>
) is commonly found, with islands of calcareous outcrops, open areas with exposed rocks, and depressions that are seasonally flooded during the rainy season (
<figureCitation id="B3FB3DBE9F31FFDAD69F5E547DF7967E" box="[643,767,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1865,1887]" captionTargetBox="[202,1435,658,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-229@5.[151,1436,605,1841]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Schwenckia aurantiaca distribution and habitat. (A) Map showing Furados (triangle), the site of the species occurrence in northern Minas Gerais, (B) Caatinga seasonally flooded during the wet season, with a view of the calcareous outcrops, (C) Caatinga with Cavanillesia umbellata Ruiz &amp; Pavón in the Serra Azul Biological Reserve, disturbed by fire during the dry season in 2007. Photographs by J.R Stehmann." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425904/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Fig. 4B–C</figureCitation>
). This seasonally dry vegetation is adapted to the semi-arid climate of the region, classified as Aw-tropical with dry winter (
<bibRefCitation id="4F515CCA9F31FFDAD7435E287B37965B" author="Reboita, M. S. &amp; Rodrigues, M. &amp; Silva, L. F. &amp; Alves, M. A." box="[863,1087,338,365]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" pagination="206 - 226" refId="ref5014" refString="Reboita, M. S., Rodrigues, M., Silva, L. F. &amp; Alves, M. A. (2015) Aspectos climaticos do estado de Minas Gerais. Revista Brasileira de Climatologia 17: 206 - 226. https: // doi. org / 10.5380 / abclima. v 17 i 0.41493" type="journal article" year="2015">
Reboita 
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD7DC5E297CF2965A" box="[960,1018,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). The temporarily flooded, open areas are the habitat of the new species, which is an annual plant. The seeds germinate in the rainy season, which is when the plant grows, reproduces, and dies, leaving seeds in the soil to germinate in the next rainy season. Anthesis observed in cultivation, is nocturnal and has a cycle that begins with the opening of the corolla lobes in the late afternoon or early evening and closing at dawn the next day, a process repeated for three consecutive days. The tubular corolla, the nocturnal anthesis, and the sweet fragrance released at night suggest that moths may be the pollinators of 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD4945D517E179572" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" box="[136,287,555,581]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD4945D517E179572" box="[136,287,555,581]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">S. aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="7FBF71B39F31FFDAD49458337E3B90FD" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425904" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5425904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425904/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" startId="5.[136,229,1865,1887]" targetBox="[202,1435,658,1841]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="2B7F213B9F31FFDAD49458337E3B90FD" blockId="5.[136,1452,1865,1995]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD49458337FF79069" bold="true" box="[136,255,1865,1887]" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">FIGURE 4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD51A58337EE09069" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" box="[262,488,1865,1887]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD51A58337EE09069" box="[262,488,1865,1887]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Schwenckia aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distribution and habitat. (A) Map showing Furados (triangle), the site of the species occurrence in northern Minas Gerais, (B) Caatinga seasonally flooded during the wet season, with a view of the calcareous outcrops, (C) Caatinga with 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F31FFDAD49458EB7EFD9091" authority="Ruiz &amp; Pavon" authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pavon" authorityYear="1798" box="[136,501,1937,1959]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Cavanillesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="5" pageNumber="171" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="umbellata">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F31FFDAD49458EB7E6F9090" box="[136,359,1937,1958]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="171">Cavanillesia umbellata</emphasis>
Ruiz &amp; Pavón
</taxonomicName>
in the Serra Azul Biological Reserve, disturbed by fire during the dry season in 2007. Photographs by J.R Stehmann.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="63DA72B09F32FFD9D4A15FE47A739586" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2B7F213B9F32FFD9D4A15FE47D4A97EA" blockId="6.[136,1452,158,689]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D4A15FE47E40978E" bold="true" box="[189,328,158,184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Etymology:</emphasis>
—The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F32FFD9D6495FE57DD8978E" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" box="[597,720,159,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D6495FE57DD8978E" box="[597,720,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” comes from Latin and means orange, an allusion to the color of the corolla appendages during anthesis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B7F213B9F32FFD9D4A15F9C7CB89636" blockId="6.[136,1452,158,689]" box="[189,944,230,257]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D4A15F9C7E4B9636" bold="true" box="[189,323,230,256]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Phenology:</emphasis>
—Flowering and fruiting occur from February to April.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B7F213B9F32FFD9D4A15E707DB79572" blockId="6.[136,1452,158,689]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D4A15E707EBE9612" bold="true" box="[189,438,266,292]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Conservation status:</emphasis>
—Critically Endangered (CR) [B1, B2b(i,iii), D]. 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F32FFD9D7EA5E707BF79612" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" box="[1014,1279,266,292]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D7EA5E707BF79612" box="[1014,1279,266,292]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Schwenckia aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from one area of Serra Azul Biological Reserve, with one or few populations (&lt;5), which are usually formed by numerous individuals (&lt;50). The Serra Azul Biological Reserve has about 
<quantity id="EC388CDE9F32FFD9D7A35E287B0D965A" box="[959,1029,338,364]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" unit="km" value="38.0">38 km</quantity>
<superScript id="DCB58C739F32FFD9D0185E287B049656" attach="left" box="[1028,1036,338,352]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">2</superScript>
and was created to protect the unique environment known as Furados, which is strongly threatened by the surrounding intensive agricultural use (irrigated fruit farming) (
<bibRefCitation id="4F515CCA9F32FFD9D52E5EE07D4A9682" author="Barbosa, R. S. &amp; Santos, F. D." box="[306,578,410,436]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" refId="ref3426" refString="Barbosa, R. S. &amp; Santos, F. D. (2008) Unidades De Conservacao, Conflitos Socioambientais e o encurralamento das Populacoes locais no Norte de Minas. In 46 th Congress, Rio Branco, Acre, Brasil. Sociedade Brasileira de Economia, Administracao e Sociologia Rural (SOBER). https: // doi. org / 10.22004 / ag. econ. 109655" type="book" year="2008">Barbosa &amp; Santos 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and by fire, already documented for the area (
<figureCitation id="B3FB3DBE9F32FFD9D0455EE07BBB9682" box="[1113,1203,410,436]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1865,1887]" captionTargetBox="[202,1435,658,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-229@5.[151,1436,605,1841]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Schwenckia aurantiaca distribution and habitat. (A) Map showing Furados (triangle), the site of the species occurrence in northern Minas Gerais, (B) Caatinga seasonally flooded during the wet season, with a view of the calcareous outcrops, (C) Caatinga with Cavanillesia umbellata Ruiz &amp; Pavón in the Serra Azul Biological Reserve, disturbed by fire during the dry season in 2007. Photographs by J.R Stehmann." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425904/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). In this environment, placed in the São Francisco river basin (
<figureCitation id="B3FB3DBE9F32FFD9D6555EC47DAB96EE" box="[585,675,446,472]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1865,1887]" captionTargetBox="[202,1435,658,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-229@5.[151,1436,605,1841]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Schwenckia aurantiaca distribution and habitat. (A) Map showing Furados (triangle), the site of the species occurrence in northern Minas Gerais, (B) Caatinga seasonally flooded during the wet season, with a view of the calcareous outcrops, (C) Caatinga with Cavanillesia umbellata Ruiz &amp; Pavón in the Serra Azul Biological Reserve, disturbed by fire during the dry season in 2007. Photographs by J.R Stehmann." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425904/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
), the species is found only in open temporarily flooded places, which correspond to an area of less than 
<quantity id="EC388CDE9F32FFD9D6055E987D5D96CA" box="[537,597,482,508]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" unit="km" value="1.0">1 km</quantity>
<superScript id="DCB58C739F32FFD9D6495E987D5596C6" attach="left" box="[597,605,482,496]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">2</superScript>
(AOO). Considering the specialized and restricted environment in which the species occurs, as well as the anthropic pressure on the Biological Reserve, our preliminary assessment for 
<taxonomicName id="ECC05AB89F32FFD9D18A5D7D7E0B9572" authorityName="Paucar &amp; Stehmann" authorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Schwenckia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">
<emphasis id="19B4FD299F32FFD9D18A5D7D7E0B9572" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="172">S. aurantiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is Critically Endangered (
<bibRefCitation id="4F515CCA9F32FFD9D6355D507DBB9572" author="IUCN Standards &amp; Petitions Committee" box="[553,691,554,580]" pageId="6" pageNumber="172" refId="ref4190" refString="IUCN Standards and Petitions Committee (2020) Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 14. Prepared by the Standards and Pettions Committee. Available from: http: // cmsdocs. s 3. amazonaws. com / (accessed 2 March 2020)" type="url" year="2020">IUCN 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
